ized form of a patronymic from the Gaelic personal name <i>Mac Raith</i> ‘son of grace or prosperity’. Compare   McGrath  , the usual Irish form of this surname."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas de Moray III was born about 1210, in Dumfriesshire, Scotland. He married Juliana de Kilconquar about 1230, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 18 May 1262, in Melrose, Roxburghshire, Scotland, at the age of 53, and was buried in Melrose, Roxburghshire, Scotland."},"et":{"about 1210–18 May 1262":"umbes 1210–18. mai 1262","1214–1262":"1214–1262","1230–1262":"1230–1262","1210–1262":"1210–1262","18 May 1262":"18. mai 1262","1214":"1214","about May 1262":"umbes mai 1262","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","estimated 1230":"umbes 1230","1262":"1262","about 1210":"umbes 1210","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Melrose, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Melrose, Roxburghshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Melrose, Selkirkshire, Scotland":"Melrose, Selkirkshire, Scotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Melrose, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Melrose, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Strathdun,,Scotland, United Kingdom":"Strathdon, Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Stranith, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1210–18 May 1262":"noin 1210–18. toukokuuta 1262","1214–1262":"1214–1262","1230–1262":"1230–1262","1210–1262":"1210–1262","18 May 1262":"18. toukokuuta 1262"